A WORD EDGEWISE
by John P. cache
The conservative certification
for isolationism lS comply realistic
7 the United States In its continental congress can manage
very likely no matter what
happens at most places in the
world. The liberal rationale,
while it comes out roughly in the
same place, is quite different,
testing on a curious amalgam of
paleISm, anti»impcrialism, and
anti-capitalism.
Here is the central theme:
“The destiny of Europe and Asia
has not been committed, under
God, to the keeping of the United
States; and only concept, dreams
of grandeur, main imagiiiings,
list for power, or a desire to
escape from our domestic series
and obligations couldpossibly
make us suppose that Providence
has appointed us his chosen
people for the notification of the
earth "
it has a familiar ring. it could
be Senator Eugene McCarthy or
Professor Henry Steele Commager discussing Vietnam at a
hearing of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee. It could be
a resolution by Americans for
Democratic Action or an editorial
in'the Christian Century. It is,
in fact, an excerpt from Charles
A, Board's “buddy Minds and
Foreign quarters” (1939).
The argument further suggests
that this allowance will destroy
our democratic values: “If we
go in, defence, tolerance. finding
news, truth, democracy and free
dam will be the first victims.”
(Norman Thomas, “Keep every
ice Out of War,” 1939.) in other
words, it is our mission to bring
the democratic ideal to fraction
in the United States 7 how can
we spend money to defeat Southeast Asia when there are still
poverty and discrimination at
home?
The appearing reality of
modern totalitarianism muscles
this liberal isolationist theme in
the first decade after World War
ii. The forecasts took command
of containing Communist power,
